Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "[DCR]: Only cancel VS cred provider requests if VS is closing" (#11970) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
### NuGet Product(s) Affected

Visual Studio Package Management UI, Visual Studio Package Manager Console

### Current Behavior

NuGet provides extensibility for credential providers, which can obtain credentials to provide feeds more intelligently than if NuGet simply asking the customer to manually enter valid credentials. In some cases this can be automatic, without prompting the customer.  There are different cred providers for command line and VS.

In VS, NuGet currently passes the same `CancellationToken` that will eventually make the HTTP request to the credential provider. This means that in scenarios where NuGet wants to cancel the HTTP request (like PM UI is closed while a pending request is waiting), NuGet will instruct the credential provider to cancel obtaining a credential.

This leads to bad experiences, because the cred provider might display a GUI and interactively pompt the customer to take an action, but then the cred provider sees the cancellation token requesting cancellation, and then doesn't cache a valid, working token. This means the next time a token is required, the cred provider needs to prompt the customer again.

Since PM UI is becoming more aggressive at cancelling HTTP requests (cancel when search query changes, cancel when PM UI closes, cancel when different package is selected in the package list so a different package is requested in the details panel), it means these bad experiences are increasing in probability.

### Desired Behavior

NuGet should allow the credential provider to complete obtaining valid credentials, unless NuGet know that it will not need valid credentials in the future. If NuGet doesn't want to wait for the credential provider to return a result, then it should find another way to exit early, without cancelling the credential provider request.

### Additional Context

_No response_

Events.RelatedBody:
### NuGet Product Used

NuGet.exe

### Product Version

NuGet Client Release-6.3.x\6.3.0.128

### Worked before?

_No response_

### Impact

_No response_

### Repro Steps & Context

## Repro steps: 
1. Git clone[ https://github.com/NuGet/Entropy.git]( https://github.com/NuGet/Entropy.git)
2. Set the following parameters in “pathOnUnix.ps1” file:
    a. The SDK channel must be: 6.0.4xx
    b. The SDK version should be:  latest
    c. Add a -Quality/--quality argument with a value of: signed
3. Cd /home/nuget/Desktop/SDKPatchTool/ and type in command './patchOnUnix.ps1'
4. Create a new test certificate: `.\CreateTestCertificate.ps1 -AddAsTrustedRootAuthority  -Password password -NotAfter "<30 minutes in the future from current local time>"  -GenerateCerFile  `
5. Sign a package: `NuGet.exe sign <PackageFilePath> -CertificatePath <PfxFilePath>` .
6. Copy the .pfx file and signed package from the above Windows machine to Mac machine.
7. Trusted Certificate:
    a. Open a Terminal window and execute:
      `  openssl pkcs12 -in <PfxFilePath> -out <PemFilePath> -nokeys`
        When prompted, enter the PFX password.
    b. Open the PEM file created in step 3.
c. Copy the entire block labelled with BEGIN CERTIFICATE/END CERTIFICATE:
-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
…
-----END CERTIFICATE-----

d. In the versioned directory of your patched .NET SDK open ./trustedroots/codesignctl.pem.
    e. At the end of the file on a new blank line, paste the copied certificate in PEM format.
    f. Save the file.
8. Create a project, add package reference in the .csproj file
  ```
<ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="<packageName>" Version="<packageVersion>" />
  </ItemGroup>
```
9. Add the feed (path contains the signed package), set required mode in nuget.config file with trusted signers list:
```
<packageSources>
      <add key="<anyname>" value="<signed package parent folder>" />
     <add key="nuget.org" value="https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json" protocolVersion="3" />
   </packageSources>
   <config>
    <add key="signatureValidationMode" value="require" />
   </config>
  <trustedSigners>
     <author name="JamieZhang">       
         <certificate fingerprint="71E8D51A3B8725197292D8CBEC76AD998A8F13F461BE778D646494FBABD974C5D050" hashAlgorithm="SHA256" allowUntrustedRoot="false" />
     </author>
  </trustedSigners>
```
10. Clear the cache: <patchedSDKPath>`./dotnet nuget locals all –clear`.
11. Delete the <projectPath>/obj folder if there is any.
12. Go inside the project folder, verify the package by running restore: `<patchedSDKPath>./dotnet restore <projectpath>/<projectname>.csproj
`
## Expected:
No error/warning shows after restoring the project since signature verification is disabled by default.

## Actual:
Unexpected error/warning show after restoring the project as below screenshot.

## Note:
We didn’t set the environment: 
export DOTNET_NUGET_SIGNATURE_VERIFICATION=true as below screenshot:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/40230425/178719386-d2291bad-e62e-4231-8379-7fe7b87932d4.png)

Events.RelatedBody: # Microsoft Security Advisory CVE 2022-30184 | .NET Information Disclosure Vulnerability ## Executive summary Microsoft is releasing this security advisory to provide information about a vulnerability in .NET 6.0 and .NET Core 3.1, NuGet (NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat version range from 3.5.0 to 6.2.0). This advisory also provides guidance on what developers can do to update their applications to remove this vulnerability. A vulnerability exists in .NET 6.0, .NET Core 3.1, and NuGet clients (NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat version range from 3.5.0 to 6.2.0) where a nuget.org credential could be leaked. ## Discussion Discussion for this issue can be found at https://github.com/nuget/home/issues. (TBD) ## Mitigation factors Microsoft has not identified any mitigating factors for this vulnerability. ## Affected software ### NuGet & NuGet Packages - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 6.2.0 version or earlier. - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 6.0.1 version or earlier. - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 5.11.1 version or earlier. - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 5.9.1 version or earlier. - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 5.7.1 version or earlier. - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 5.2.0 version or earlier. - Any NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat 4.9.4 version or earlier. ### .NET SDK(s) - Any .NET 6.0 application running on .NET 6.0.5 or earlier. - Any .NET 3.1 application running on .NET Core 3.1.25 or earlier. ### How do I know if I am affected? If you have a NuGet.exe, NuGet package, or .NET SDK with a version listed in [affected software](#affected-software), you're exposed to the vulnerability. ### How do I fix the issue? To fix the issue, please install the latest version of .NET 6.0 or .NET Core 3.1 and NuGet (NuGet.exe, NuGet.Commands, NuGet.CommandLine, NuGet.CommandLine.XPlat version 4.9.5, 5.7.2, 5.9.2, 5.11.2, 6.0.2, 6.2.1). If you have installed one or more .NET SDKs through Visual Studio, Visual Studio will prompt you to update Visual Studio, which will also update your .NET SDKs. You can get the version of NuGet.exe by running the `nuget` command.
